-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
x86-64 System V ABI
-------------------

The ABI is just a specification document, which specifies:

- ISA (Instruction Set Architecture) - what instructions exist (mov, add,
  syscall, etc.)
- ABI (Application Binary Interface) - how functions call each other
  (registers, stack layout, return values)
- OS conventions - Mach-O on macOS vs ELF on Linux, symbol naming, system
  calls, etc.

One can read the official doc from here:
    "System V Application Binary Interface AMD64 Architecture Processor Supplement"
    https://refspecs.linuxbase.org/elf/x86_64-abi-0.99.pdf

    This document defines things like:

        Integer args:
            1 → rdi
            2 → rsi
            3 → rdx
            4 → rcx
            5 → r8
            6 → r9

        Return:
            rax

        Stack:
            16-byte aligned before call

        Callee-saved:
            rbx
            rbp
            r12-r15

        Caller-saved:
            rax
            rcx
            rdx
            rdi
            rsi
            r8-r11

There's also this docuemnt from Apple:
    "Writing 64-bit Intel code for Apple Platforms"
    https://developer.apple.com/documentation/xcode/writing-64-bit-intel-code-for-apple-platforms


One can also see what the compiler generates:

    long add(long a, long b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    ...

    $ clang -S add.c

    _add:
    movq    %rdi, %rax  # rdi: first arg
    addq    %rsi, %rax  # rsi: second arg, rax: return value
    retq


One can also use tools such as objdump, nm, or otool

    nm main.o
    objdump -d main.o
    objdump -D main.o
    objdump -tC main.o
    otool -tvV demo

These tools let you inspect exactly what symbols and instructions were
generated.


Note on ISA: The ABI only says: put first argument in rdi. It does NOT teach
you:

    lea
    mov
    imul
    shl
    cmp
    jmp
    cmov

For that, read:

    Intel Software Developer Manuals
    AMD64 Architecture Programmer's Manuals

There are also syntax flavours.

    Intel syntax examples:

        mov rax, rdi
        add rax, rsi
        ret

    AT&T syntax (what Clang emits):

        movq %rdi, %rax
        addq %rsi, %rax
        ret

These are same instructions.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Special Registers in x86-64
---------------------------

Unlike general-purpose registers (RAX, RBX, RCX, etc.), some registers have
special roles that the CPU and calling conventions rely upon.

RSP - Stack Pointer

    Purpose: RSP points to the top of the current stack.

    The stack grows downward in memory:

        ```
        Higher addresses
        +-------------+
        |     ...     |
        +-------------+
        | local vars  |
        +-------------+
        | return addr |
        +-------------+ <-- RSP
        |      ↓      |
        |     ...     |
        Lower addresses
        ```

    The stack is used for:

        * Function call return addresses
        * Saving registers
        * Local variables
        * Temporaries
        * Passing extra arguments

    Common Instructions

        Push a value:

            ```
            push rax
            ```

        Equivalent to:

            ```
            sub rsp, 8
            mov [rsp], rax
            ```

        Pop a value:

            ```
            pop rax
            ```

        Equivalent to:

            ```
            mov rax, [rsp]
            add rsp, 8
            ```

        Allocate stack space:

            ```
            sub rsp, 32
            ```

        Release stack space:

            ```
            add rsp, 32
            ```

        Access local variables:

            ```
            mov rax, [rsp]
            mov rax, [rsp + 8]
            mov [rsp + 16], rcx
            ```

        Function calls also use RSP:

            ```
            call func
            ```

        The CPU effectively performs:

            ```
            push rip
            jmp func
            ```

        Return:

            ```
            ret
            ```

        The CPU effectively performs:

            ```
            pop rip
            ```

    ABI Requirements

        In the x86-64 System V ABI:

            * Stack must be 16-byte {align}ed before a call instruction.
            * The caller usually adjusts RSP.
            * Most functions temporarily modify RSP to create a stack frame.

        Example:

            ```
            sub rsp, 32
            ...
            add rsp, 32
            ret
            ```

RBP - Base Pointer (Frame Pointer)

    Purpose: RBP traditionally marks the beginning of a function's stack frame.

    Example:

        Before call:

            ```
            +----------------+
            | caller data    |
            +----------------+
            ```

        After {prologue}:

            ```
            push rbp
            mov rbp, rsp
            sub rsp, 32
            ```

        Stack becomes:

            ```
            Higher addresses

            arg n
            ...
            return address
            saved rbp      <-- RBP
            local variable
            local variable <-- RSP

            Lower addresses
            ```

        RBP provides stable offsets:

            ```
            [rbp + 8]   return address
            [rbp + 16]  first stack argument
            [rbp - 8]   local variable
            [rbp - 16]  local variable
            ```

    Common Instructions

        Save old frame pointer:

            ```
            push rbp
            ```

        Create frame:

            ```
            mov rbp, rsp
            ```

        Access locals:

            ```
            mov rax, [rbp - 8]
            ```

        Access stack arguments:

            ```
            mov rax, [rbp + 16]
            ```

        Destroy frame:

            ```
            mov rsp, rbp
            pop rbp
            ret
            ```

    Modern Compilers

        Compilers often omit frame pointers:

            ```
            -fomit-frame-pointer
            ```

        and simply use RSP directly.

            This frees RBP as another general-purpose register.


RIP - Instruction Pointer

    Purpose: RIP contains the address of the next instruction to execute.

    Example:

            Address      Instruction
            ---
            1000         mov rax, 5
            1007         add rax, 3
            100B         ret

        Execution:

            RIP = 1000
            execute mov

            RIP = 1007
            execute add

            RIP = 100B
            execute ret

        You normally cannot directly write:

            ```
            mov rip, rax
            ```

        because RIP is not a normal register.

    Instructions That Modify RIP

        Unconditional jump:

            ```
            jmp label
            ```

        Conditional jump:

            ```
            je label
            jne label
            jg label
            jl label
            ```

        Function call:

            ```
            call func
            ```

        Function return:

            ```
            ret
            ```

        Indirect jump:

            ```
            jmp rax
            ```

        Indirect call:

            ```
            call rax
            ```

    RIP-Relative Addressing

        One of the major improvements in x86-64.

        Example:

            ```
            lea rax, [rip + message]
            ```

        This computes:

            ```
            rax = address_of_message
            ```

        This allows position-independent code (PIC), shared libraries, and
        ASLR.


RFLAGS - Flag Register

    Purpose: RFLAGS stores status information about previous operations.

    The CPU automatically updates flags after many instructions.

    ## Important Flags

            CF - Carry Flag
            ZF - Zero Flag
            SF - Sign Flag
            OF - Overflow Flag
            PF - Parity Flag

        Most programs primarily use:

            CF
            ZF
            SF
            OF

    Zero Flag (ZF)

        Set when result is zero.

        Example:

            ```
            mov rax, 5
            sub rax, 5
            ```

        Result:

            ```
            rax = 0
            ZF = 1
            ```

        Used by:

            ```
            je
            jne
            cmove
            cmovne
            ```

    Carry Flag (CF)

        Indicates unsigned overflow.

        Example:

            ```
            mov al, 255
            add al, 1
            ```

        Result:

            ```
            al = 0
            CF = 1
            ```

        Used by:

            ```
            jc
            jnc
            adc
            sbb
            ```

    Sign Flag (SF)

        Set if result is negative.

        Example:

            ```
            mov rax, 3
            sub rax, 5
            ```

        Result:

            ```
            rax = -2
            SF = 1
            ```

        Used by:

            ```
            js
            jns
            jl
            jge
            ```

    Overflow Flag (OF)

        Indicates signed overflow.

        Example:

            ```
            mov al, 127
            add al, 1
            ```

        Result:

            ```
            al = -128
            OF = 1
            ```

        Used by:

            ```
            jo
            jno
            jl
            jg
            jle
            jge
            ```


Instructions That Set Flags

    Arithmetic:

        ```
        add
        sub
        inc
        dec
        adc
        sbb
        neg
        ```

    Comparison:

        ```
        cmp
        ```

    Logical:

        ```
        and
        or
        xor
        test
        ```

    Shift operations:

        ```
        shl
        shr
        sar
        ```

    Example:

        ```
        cmp rax, rbx
        je equal
        ```

    Equivalent to:

        ```
        sub rax, rbx
        discard result
        examine flags
        ```


Conditional Jumps

    After:

        ```
        cmp rax, rbx
        ```

    Instructions may inspect flags:

        ```
        je     ZF == 1
        jne    ZF == 0
        jl     SF != OF
        jle    ZF == 1 or SF != OF
        jg     ZF == 0 and SF == OF
        jge    SF == OF
        jb     CF == 1
        jbe    CF == 1 or ZF == 1
        ja      CF == 0 and ZF == 0
        jae     CF == 0
        ```

    Signed comparisons generally use:

        ```
        SF
        OF
        ZF
        ```

    Unsigned comparisons generally use:

        ```
        CF
        ZF
        ```


Typical Function Execution

    Caller:

        ```
        call add
        ```

    CPU:

        ```
        push return_address
        rip = address_of_add
        ```

    Function:

        ```
        push rbp
        mov rbp, rsp
        sub rsp, 32

        cmp rdi, rsi
        jl smaller
        ```

        ```
        smaller:
        mov rsp, rbp
        pop rbp
        ret
        ```

    CPU:

        ```
        pop rip
        ```

    Execution resumes at the instruction after the original call.


Summary

    RSP
        Stack pointer.
        Modified by push, pop, call, ret, sub/add rsp.

    RBP
        Frame pointer.
        Used for stable stack frame references.

    RIP
        Instruction pointer.
        Modified by jmp, call, ret, conditional jumps.

    RFLAGS
        Status register.
        Set by arithmetic, comparison, logical, and shift instructions.
        Read by conditional jumps and conditional moves.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Debugging using LLDB
--------------------

    $ lldb ./a.out

    # set breakpoint

        (lldb) breakpoint set --name main
        (lldb) b main

    # Break at your assembly function (Important: macOS adds _ prefix)

        (lldb) b _add

    # Break at a specific instruction (assembly level)

        # First disassemble:
        (lldb) disassemble --name _add

        # Then set breakpoint by address if needed:
        (lldb) b *0x100003f20

    # Run program. Execution then stops at breakpoint.

        (lldb) run

    # Usual operations: step into, over, ...
    # Once inside _add

        (lldb) stepi # or is - step by step instruction
        (lldb) nexti # - step over (function-level)

        (lldb) disassemble --frame # View assembly around current instruction
        (lldb) disassemble --pc # more verbose

    # Inspect registers (VERY important for your use case)

        # Show all registers
        (lldb) register read

        # Show specific registers
        (lldb) register read rax rdi rsi rip rsp rbp

        # Watch register changes while stepping: just keep doing:
        (lldb) register read rax rip

    # Inspect memory (stack debugging)

        # Examine stack pointer:
        (lldb) memory read $rsp

        # Read 64-bit words:
        (lldb) memory read -f x -s 8 -c 8 $rsp

            # Meaning:
            # -f x → hex
            # -s 8 → 8-byte chunks
            # -c 8 → 8 values

    # See function arguments (important for ABI learning)

        # For x86-64 System V:
        #     arg1 -> rdi
        #     arg2 -> rsi
        # So:
        (lldb) register read rdi rsi

    # Step back into C and assembly together

        # If you break in main:
        (lldb) b main
        (lldb) run

        # Then:
        (lldb) disassemble --frame

        # You’ll see call instruction:

            callq _add

        # Step into it:
        (lldb) si

        # Now you're inside assembly.

    # View mixed C + assembly

        (lldb) disassemble --mixed

        # This is extremely useful when debugging C calling assembly.

    # Watch variables (C side)

        (lldb) frame variable

        # or
        (lldb) p x
        (lldb) p y


Typical workflow for your setup

    When debugging C + assembly like yours:

    1. breakpoint main
    2. run
    3. step to call _add
    4. step into _add
    5. si (single-step assembly)
    6. register read rax rdi rsi rip
    7. disassemble --frame


ADVANCED (later)

    how to debug stack frames manually (prologue/epilogue)
    how call / ret actually modify rsp in LLDB step-by-step
    or how to break on every instruction automatically (trace mode)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Intel vs AT&T syntax
--------------------

Again remember:

    ABI = “how functions talk”
    ISA = “what CPU understands”
    Syntax = “how humans write assembly”

A comparison

    AT&T syntax (default on macOS)

        movq %rdi, %rax
        addq %rsi, %rax

    Intel syntax

        mov rax, rdi
        add rax, rsi

    Key differences:

        | Concept    | AT&T           | Intel             |
        | ---------- | -------------- | ----------------- |
        | registers  | `%rax`         | `rax`             |
        | immediates | `$5`           | `5`               |
        | order      | `src, dst`     | `dst, src`        |
        | suffix     | `movq`, `addq` | just `mov`, `add` |

How to write Intel syntax on macOS: two options

    1. use Clang + .intel_syntax (recommended)

        add.s:

            .intel_syntax noprefix

            .text
            .globl _add

            _add:
                mov rax, rdi
                add rax, rsi
                ret


        .intel_syntax noprefix → enables Intel syntax
        noprefix removes % requirement (so rax instead of %rax)


    2. use GAS explicitly (GNU assembler style)

       On macOS, as is still LLVM integrated, but supports Intel mode
       similarly:

           .intel_syntax noprefix

       works the same.


    3. One could also force Intel syntax via compiler flags

        ASFLAGS = -masm=intel

       But on macos, -masm=intel is not consistently supported for Mach-O
       toolchain. .intel_syntax is the reliable method


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Basic Instructions
------------------

Below are minimal Intel-syntax examples + inline comments only for each
instruction.

MOV

    mov rax, rdi      ; copy value from rdi into rax (rax = rdi)
    mov rbx, 10       ; load immediate constant 10 into rbx
    mov [rsp], rax    ; store rax into memory at address rsp
    mov rax, [rsp]    ; load value from memory at rsp into rax

ADD

    add rax, rsi      ; rax = rax + rsi
    add rax, 5        ; rax = rax + 5
    add [rsp], rax    ; memory[rsp] = memory[rsp] + rax

SUB

    sub rax, rsi      ; rax = rax - rsi
    sub rax, 10       ; rax = rax - 10
    sub rsp, 32       ; move stack pointer down (allocate stack space)

INC

    inc rax           ; rax = rax + 1
    inc qword [rsp]   ; increment 8-byte value in memory at rsp

DEC

    dec rax           ; rax = rax - 1
    dec byte [rbx]    ; decrement 1-byte value at address rbx

XCHG

    xchg rax, rbx     ; swap rax and rbx
    xchg rax, [rsp]   ; swap rax with memory at rsp

RET
    ret               ; pop return address from stack into rip and jump back

Equivalent conceptual behavior:

    rip = [rsp]
    rsp = rsp + 8
    jump to rip


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Jumps, Labels and the Compare Instruction
-----------------------------------------

1. Labels

    Labels are just **named memory addresses**.

        start:              ; label = address of this instruction
            mov rax, 1      ; normal instruction
            mov rbx, 2

        loop_begin:         ; another label (a jump target)
            inc rax

    Key idea: A label is NOT an instruction. It becomes an address after
    assembly.

2. Unconditional Jump (JMP)

        jmp start          ; RIP = address of "start"

    With label:

        mov rax, 0
        jmp skip           ; jump forward unconditionally
        mov rax, 999       ; skipped
        skip:              ; execution continues here
            inc rax

3. Conditional Jumps

    These depend on **RFLAGS** (set by CMP, ADD, SUB, etc.).

    Example: equality

        mov rax, 5
        mov rbx, 5

        cmp rax, rbx       ; sets flags (rax - rbx)

        je equal           ; jump if equal (ZF = 1)

        mov rcx, 0         ; executed only if not equal
        jmp done

        equal:
            mov rcx, 1     ; executed if equal

        done:

    Common conditional jumps

        je  label   ; equal (ZF = 1)
        jne label   ; not equal (ZF = 0)

        jg  label   ; greater (signed)
        jl  label   ; less (signed)

        ja  label   ; above (unsigned)
        jb  label   ; below (unsigned)

4. CMP instruction

    `CMP` = subtraction without storing result.

        cmp rax, rbx      ; computes rax - rbx internally
                          ; result is NOT stored
                          ; only flags are updated

    Equivalent conceptual model:

        tmp = rax - rbx
        set FLAGS based on tmp
        discard tmp

    Example usage:

        mov rax, 10
        mov rbx, 20

        cmp rax, rbx      ; 10 - 20 → negative result

        jl smaller        ; jump if rax < rbx

    Loop using CMP + Jumps

        mov rcx, 5

        loop_start:
            dec rcx           ; rcx = rcx - 1
            cmp rcx, 0        ; check if rcx == 0
            jne loop_start    ; repeat if not zero


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What CAN and CANNOT be operands?
--------------------------------

Allowed operand types

    1. Registers

        mov rax, rbx
        add rax, rsi

    2. Immediate values (constants)

        mov rax, 10
        add rbx, 5

    3. Memory operands

        mov rax, [rsp]        ; load from memory
        mov [rsp], rax        ; store to memory

    4. Register + offset memory

        mov rax, [rbp - 8]    ; local variable
        mov rbx, [rdi + 16]   ; struct field

    5. RIP-relative (x86-64 only)

        mov rax, [rip + label] ; position-independent access

What CANNOT be operands?

    1. Memory-to-memory operations are NOT allowed

            mov [rax], [rbx]     ; INVALID
            add [rsp], [rbp]     ; INVALID

        You must use a register:

            mov rax, [rbx]
            mov [rsp], rax

    2. Immediate to memory for some instructions is limited

        Some CPUs allow it, but general rule:

            add [rsp], 10        ; sometimes valid but not universal pattern

        Safe pattern:

            mov rax, [rsp]
            add rax, 10
            mov [rsp], rax

    3. You cannot use RIP directly as a normal operand

            mov rip, rax         ; NOT POSSIBLE

        RIP is only modified by:

        * jmp
        * call
        * ret
        * conditional jumps

    4. CMP does not produce a value

            mov rax, cmp rbx, rcx   ; INVALID

        Correct:

            cmp rbx, rcx


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Memory and pointers
-------------------

Flat Memory Model
    -> https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flat_memory_model

    Modern x86-64 uses a **flat {virtual address space}**.
    -> https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_address_space

    Conceptually:

        0x0000000000000000
                ...
                Code (.text)
                Read-only data (.rodata)
                Global data (.data)
                Heap
                ...
                Stack
        0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF

    A pointer is simply an **address** somewhere in this space.

    Unlike the old 8086 segmented model (`segment:offset`), in x86-64 you
    generally think:

        physical address ≈ virtual address (after MMU translation)
        pointer = 64-bit address

    No manual segment arithmetic.


Addresses vs Values

        mov rbx, 5

    puts the **number 5** into `rbx`, i.e., rbx = 0x5.

    Whether you treat `5` as an integer or an address is entirely up to you.


Dereferencing

        mov cl, [rbx]

    means: cl = memory[rbx].

    Since rbx = 5, it means: cl = memory[0x5]

    This will almost certainly crash in {user-space} because address `0x5` is
    invalid.


Why `byte ptr` exists

        mov cl, [rbx]

    is okay because destination (`cl`) already tells the assembler: size = 1 byte.

    Equivalently:

        mov cl, byte ptr [rbx]

    But here:

        mov [rbx], 11

    the assembler doesn't know:

        * store 1 byte?
        * store 2 bytes?
        * store 4 bytes?
        * store 8 bytes?

    So you must specify:

        mov byte ptr [rbx], 11

    meaning: memory[rbx] = 11 (1 byte)


Pointer Sizes

    *    byte ptr:  1 byte
    *    word ptr:  2 bytes
    *   dword ptr:  4 bytes
    *   qword ptr:  8 bytes
    * xmmword ptr: 16 bytes
    * ymmword ptr: 32 bytes

        mov       al,    byte ptr [rbx]
        mov       ax,    word ptr [rbx]
        mov      eax,   dword ptr [rbx]
        mov      rax,   qword ptr [rbx]
        movdqu  xmm0, xmmword ptr [rbx]
        vmovdqu ymm0, ymmword ptr [rbx]


Memory is untyped

    Assembly sees memory like this:

        Address     Bytes
        1000        ??
        1001        ??
        1002        ??
        1003        ??

    The CPU does **not** know:

        * int
        * short
        * float
        * struct
        * string

    You decide how many bytes to read.


LEA - Load Effective Address

        lea rax, [rbx + 8]  ; rax = rbx + 8

    No memory access occurs.

    Equivalent to:

        ```cpp
        p = q + 8;
        ```

    NOT:

        ```cpp
        p = *q;
        ```


# What is an Effective Address?

    My explanation (take it with a grain of pepper): Assembler/Compiler does
    not know in priori where the exact location of the allocated memory, that
    is the start of the data section, is. Only after the program is loaded by
    the loader, that location in memory is known. Because of that we can only
    talk about memory in data section via an offset. LEA instruciton comes to
    light to get us the actuall, or effective, address in the virtual memory.


Why RIP-relative addressing?


    Programs are loaded at different addresses because of Address Space Layout
    Randomization, ASLR.
    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Address_space_layout_randomization

    Today: program base = 0x100000000

    Tomorrow: program base = 0x104800000

    The compiler cannot hardcode absolute addresses. Instead:

        ```asm
        lea rax, [rip + _x]
        ```

    which means:

        ```text
        current instruction address
        + offset to x
        ```

    which works regardless of where the loader placed the program.


C++ vs Assembly Pointers

    C++

            ```cpp
            int *p;
            ```

        Compiler knows:

            type      = int
            sizeof    = 4
            *p        = read 4 bytes
            p + 1     = add 4

        Types matter.

        Example:

            ```cpp
            int *p;
            p++;
            ```

        Compiler generates: p = p + 4

    Assembly

        Assembly only sees:

            ```asm
            mov rbx, address
            ```

        `rbx` is just: 64-bit integer. No type.

        You decide:

            ```asm
            mov al, [rbx]      ; 1 byte
            mov ax, [rbx]      ; 2 bytes
            mov eax, [rbx]     ; 4 bytes
            mov rax, [rbx]     ; 8 bytes
            ```

        Likewise:

            ```asm
            add rbx, 1
            add rbx, 4
            add rbx, 128
            ```

        All are equally valid. The CPU has no idea whether `rbx` points to:

        * int
        * float
        * char
        * struct
        * array

        Those concepts exist only in higher-level languages.


Mental Model

    C++:
        pointer = address + type

    Assembly:
        pointer = address only

    and

        MOV [addr]  -> read/write memory
        LEA [addr]  -> compute address only


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Calling Convention
------------------

A **calling convention** is a set of rules that answers:

    "When function A calls function B, how are arguments passed, and how is the
    return value handled?"

It defines things like:

    * Where arguments go (registers vs stack)
    * Where return values go
    * Which registers must be preserved
    * How the stack is managed across calls

So it’s specifically about **function calls**.

    Note: an **ABI (Application Binary Interface)**, is a much broader
          contract.

          It includes:

          * Calling conventions (yes, inside it)
          * Register usage rules
          * Stack alignment rules
          * Binary format (Mach-O on macOS)
          * Name mangling rules (C++ especially)
          * System interfaces (syscalls, etc.)
          * Data layout (struct alignment, sizeof rules)

          ABI                = full binary-level contract
          Calling convention = one part of the ABI (function calls only)

          ABI                = "how binaries work together"
          Calling convention = "how functions talk to each other"

On macOS Intel (or Rosetta x86-64), the calling convention is:

    **System V AMD64 ABI (with Mach-O naming rules)**

Argument passing rules (integers / pointers)

    * First 6 integer/pointer arguments:

        | Argument | Register |
        | -------- | -------- |
        | 1st      | rdi      |
        | 2nd      | rsi      |
        | 3rd      | rdx      |
        | 4th      | rcx      |
        | 5th      | r8       |
        | 6th      | r9       |

    * After that → stack.

    * Return value:

        | Type              | Register |
        | ----------------- | -------- |
        | integer / pointer | rax      |

    ---

    Example in C++

        ```cpp
        long add(long a, long b) {
            return a + b;
        }
        ```

    Assembly view:

        ```asm
        mov rax, rdi   ; a
        add rax, rsi   ; b
        ret
        ```

    Example call site:

        ```cpp
        add(10, 20);
        ```

    becomes:

        ```asm
        mov rdi, 10
        mov rsi, 20
        call _add
        ```

Stack alignment rule (important detail)

    Before a `call`, the stack must be: **16-byte aligned**

    So compilers often adjust:

        ```asm
        sub rsp, 8
        call _add
        add rsp, 8
        ```

    This ensures SIMD instructions (SSE/AVX) behave correctly.

MacOS naming rule (Mach-O specific)

    On macOS:

        ```text
        C/C++ function: add
        assembly symbol: _add
        ```

    So:

        ```asm
        .globl _add
        _add:
        ```

    C++ sees:

        ```cpp
        extern "C" long add(long, long);
        ```

    The linker maps:

        ```text
        add  -> _add
        ```

Passing integers from C++ → Assembly

    C++ code:

        ```cpp
        extern "C" long add(long a, long b);

        int main() {
            long x = add(3, 7);
        }
        ```

    Assembly:

        ```asm
        .globl _add

        _add:
            mov rax, rdi    ; a
            add rax, rsi    ; b
            ret
        ```

Returning integers from Assembly → C++

    Return is always:

        ```text
        rax
        ```

    Example:

        ```asm
        mov rax, 42
        ret
        ```

    C++:

        ```cpp
        long x = add();
        ```

Passing more than 6 arguments

    Extra arguments go on the stack:

        ```cpp
        foo(a,b,c,d,e,f,g);
        ```

    Registers:

        ```
        rdi rsi rdx rcx r8 r9
        ```

    Then:

        ```
        g → stack
        ```

Stack-based argument example (conceptual)

    ```asm
    mov rdi, 1
    mov rsi, 2
    mov rdx, 3
    mov rcx, 4
    mov r8,  5
    mov r9,  6

    push 7
    call _foo
    ```

What registers must be preserved?

    Caller-saved (volatile)

        These may be overwritten by called functions:

            rax, rcx, rdx, rsi, rdi, r8, r9, r10, r11

    Callee-saved (must preserve if used)

            rbx, rbp, r12, r13, r14, r15

        So if your assembly uses `rbx`, you must do:

            ```asm
            push rbx
            ...
            pop rbx
            ```

Minimal C++ ↔ Assembly integer interface

    Assembly function:

        ```asm
        .globl _mul_add

        _mul_add:
            ; (a,b,c) = rdi, rsi, rdx
            mov rax, rdi
            imul rax, rsi
            add rax, rdx
            ret
        ```

    C++:

        ```cpp
        extern "C" long mul_add(long a, long b, long c);

        long x = mul_add(2, 3, 4);
        ```

Key mental model

    Think of function calls like this:

        C++ caller:
            puts values into registers
            jumps (call)

        Assembly callee:
            reads registers
            computes
            puts result in rax
            returns

One-line summary

    * **Calling convention** = rules for function calls (args, return, registers)
    * **ABI** = full binary contract (includes calling convention + more)
    * On macOS x86-64: uses **System V AMD64 ABI**
    * Integers:
      * args → rdi, rsi, rdx, rcx, r8, r9
      * return → rax


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
History of x86 / AMD64 Processors
-----------------------------------

1978 - Intel 8086

    * First x86 processor.
    * 16-bit CPU.
    * 20-bit address bus (1 MB address space).
    * Introduced segmented memory:
      physical = segment * 16 + offset
    * Registers:
      AX BX CX DX
      SP BP SI DI
      CS DS ES SS
    * Foundation of the x86 instruction set.

1979 - Intel 8088

    * Internally same architecture as 8086.
    * External data bus reduced to 8 bits.
    * Cheaper system designs.
    * Used in the original IBM PC (1981).
    * Responsible for x86 becoming the dominant PC architecture.

1982 - Intel 80286 (286)

    * 16-bit CPU.
    * Introduced Protected Mode.
    * 24-bit addressing (16 MB).
    * Added memory protection and privilege levels.
    * Intended for multitasking operating systems.
    * Still had compatibility issues with DOS.

1985 - Intel 80386 (386)

    * Huge milestone.
    * First 32-bit x86 processor.
    * Registers expanded:
      EAX EBX ECX EDX
      ESP EBP ESI EDI
    * 32-bit address space (4 GB).
    * Added paging and virtual memory.
    * Protected mode became practical.
    * Basis of modern operating systems.

1989 - Intel 80486 (486)

    * Improved 386 architecture.
    * Added on-chip floating-point unit (on most models).
    * Added on-chip cache.
    * Added pipelining.
    * Much higher performance without changing ISA.

1993 - Pentium (P5)

    * Superscalar execution.
    * Two instruction pipelines.
    * Wider memory bus.
    * Better branch prediction.
    * Significantly improved floating-point performance.

1995 - Pentium Pro (P6)

    * Out-of-order execution.
    * Register renaming.
    * Speculative execution.
    * Dynamic scheduling.
    * Modern CPU microarchitecture concepts appear.

1997 - Pentium II

    * Improved P6 design.
    * Added MMX instructions.
    * Better multimedia performance.

1999 - Pentium III

    * Added SSE instructions.
    * SIMD became increasingly important.

2000 - Pentium 4 (NetBurst)

    * Very deep pipeline.
    * Extremely high clock frequencies.
    * Added SSE2.
    * Poor power efficiency.
    * Eventually considered a dead-end design.


...
Meanwhile: AMD enters the picture
...


1996 - AMD K5

    * AMD's first in-house x86 processor.

1997 - AMD K6

    * Competitive with Intel's Pentium line.
    * Helped AMD become a serious x86 competitor.

1999 - AMD Athlon (K7)

    * Extremely competitive performance.
    * Often beat Intel's Pentium III and Pentium 4.

2003 - AMD64 (x86-64)

    * One of the most important moments in processor history.
    * AMD extends x86 to 64 bits.
    * Registers become:
      RAX RBX RCX RDX
      RSP RBP RSI RDI
    * Adds:
      R8-R15
    * 64-bit pointers.
    * More registers.
    * Better calling conventions.
    * Backward compatible with 32-bit and 16-bit code.


...
Intel initially pursued a different architecture: IA-64 (Itanium)
    Itanium failed commercially.
    Intel eventually adopted AMD's extensions.

Intel implementation names:
    EM64T
    Intel 64

Today: AMD64, x86-64, Intel 64 all refer to essentially the same ISA.
...


2006 - Intel Core Architecture

    * Replaced NetBurst.
    * Shorter pipelines.
    * Better power efficiency.
    * Based partly on lessons from Pentium Pro.

2008 - Intel Nehalem

    * Integrated memory controller.
    * Hyper-Threading returns.
    * Large performance improvements.

2011 - Intel Sandy Bridge

    * Major architectural improvement.
    * Strong single-threaded performance.
    * Became one of the most successful Intel generations.

2013+ - Haswell, Skylake, and successors

    * Incremental improvements.
    * AVX and AVX2 expansion.
    * Better branch prediction.
    * Larger caches.
    * Increasing focus on power efficiency.


...
AMD Revival
...


2017 - AMD Zen

    * Massive architectural redesign.
    * Competitive IPC.
    * High core counts.
    * Restored competition in x86 CPUs.

2019 - Zen 2

    * Chiplet architecture.
    * Major efficiency gains.

2020 - Zen 3

    * Significant IPC improvements.
    * Industry-leading performance.

2022+ - Zen 4 and later

    * AVX-512 support on many models.
    * Higher frequencies.
    * Continued refinement of x86-64.

...
Present Day

    Modern x86-64 CPUs are descendants of the 8086.

    The remarkable property of x86 is backward compatibility:
    8086 → 286 → 386 → 486 → Pentium → AMD64 → Zen/Core

    A modern x86-64 processor can still execute code written for the original
    8086, even though internally it uses:

    * deep pipelines
    * out-of-order execution
    * register renaming
    * speculative execution
    * SIMD units
    * multiple cores
    * complex cache hierarchies

    Architecturally, today's CPUs still expose an ISA whose ancestry can be
    traced directly back to the Intel 8086 released in 1978.
